<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <title>Dzukku Platform Brochure</title>
  <style>
    @page {
      size: A4;
      margin: 18mm 16mm;
    }

    :root {
      --ink: #17212b;
      --muted: #5f6b78;
      --line: #d9e1e8;
      --brand: #b72b35;
      --brand-dark: #7d1821;
      --gold: #c48a2c;
      --green: #16795b;
      --blue: #2764a8;
      --bg: #f7f4ee;
      --panel: #ffffff;
    }

    * {
      box-sizing: border-box;
    }

    body {
      margin: 0;
      background: var(--bg);
      color: var(--ink);
      font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
      line-height: 1.48;
      font-size: 10.8pt;
    }

    .page {
      max-width: 980px;
      margin: 0 auto;
      background: var(--panel);
      min-height: 100vh;
    }

    .hero {
      padding: 42px 46px 34px;
      color: #fff;
      background:
        linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(125, 24, 33, 0.96), rgba(23, 33, 43, 0.92)),
        radial-gradient(circle at 82% 16%, rgba(196, 138, 44, 0.55), transparent 34%);
    }

    .eyebrow {
      margin: 0 0 18px;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 2px;
      font-weight: 700;
      font-size: 9pt;
      color: #f7d794;
    }

    h1 {
      margin: 0;
      max-width: 760px;
      font-size: 37pt;
      line-height: 1.02;
      letter-spacing: 0;
    }

    .subtitle {
      max-width: 780px;
      margin: 18px 0 0;
      color: #f7efe8;
      font-size: 14pt;
      line-height: 1.42;
    }

    .hero-grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
      gap: 10px;
      margin-top: 30px;
    }

    .hero-stat {
      border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.28);
      padding: 13px 12px;
      border-radius: 8px;
      background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.09);
    }

    .hero-stat strong {
      display: block;
      font-size: 15pt;
      color: #fff;
      margin-bottom: 4px;
    }

    .hero-stat span {
      color: #f4dccb;
      font-size: 9pt;
    }

    main {
      padding: 34px 46px 48px;
    }

    section {
      margin: 0 0 30px;
      break-inside: avoid;
    }

    h2 {
      margin: 0 0 12px;
      color: var(--brand-dark);
      font-size: 20pt;
      letter-spacing: 0;
    }

    h3 {
      margin: 18px 0 8px;
      color: #26313c;
      font-size: 13.5pt;
    }

    p {
      margin: 0 0 10px;
    }

    ul {
      margin: 8px 0 0 20px;
      padding: 0;
    }

    li {
      margin: 4px 0;
    }

    .lead {
      color: #374656;
      font-size: 12.2pt;
      line-height: 1.55;
    }

    .grid-2 {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
      gap: 14px;
    }

    .grid-3 {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
      gap: 12px;
    }

    .card {
      border: 1px solid var(--line);
      border-radius: 8px;
      padding: 15px;
      background: #fff;
      break-inside: avoid;
    }

    .card h3 {
      margin-top: 0;
      color: var(--brand-dark);
    }

    .badge-row {
      display: flex;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
      gap: 7px;
      margin: 13px 0 0;
    }

    .badge {
      display: inline-block;
      padding: 5px 8px;
      border-radius: 999px;
      background: #f1f5f8;
      color: #26313c;
      border: 1px solid #dde7ee;
      font-size: 9pt;
      font-weight: 700;
    }

    .callout {
      padding: 16px 18px;
      border-left: 5px solid var(--gold);
      background: #fff8ea;
      border-radius: 6px;
      color: #3d3020;
    }

    .ai-flow {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(5, 1fr);
      gap: 8px;
      margin-top: 12px;
    }

    .step {
      min-height: 92px;
      padding: 11px 10px;
      border-radius: 8px;
      border: 1px solid #dce5eb;
      background: #f8fafb;
    }

    .step strong {
      display: block;
      color: var(--blue);
      margin-bottom: 5px;
      font-size: 10pt;
    }

    table {
      width: 100%;
      border-collapse: collapse;
      margin: 10px 0 0;
      font-size: 9.7pt;
    }

    th, td {
      border: 1px solid var(--line);
      padding: 8px 9px;
      vertical-align: top;
      text-align: left;
    }

    th {
      background: #eef3f6;
      color: #22303c;
    }

    .pill {
      display: inline-block;
      color: #fff;
      background: var(--green);
      border-radius: 999px;
      padding: 3px 8px;
      font-size: 8.8pt;
      font-weight: 700;
      white-space: nowrap;
    }

    .architecture {
      font-family: "Courier New", monospace;
      background: #101820;
      color: #eaf2f8;
      border-radius: 8px;
      padding: 16px;
      font-size: 8.6pt;
      line-height: 1.45;
      white-space: pre-wrap;
      overflow-wrap: anywhere;
    }

    .footer {
      margin-top: 26px;
      padding-top: 16px;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
      color: var(--muted);
      font-size: 9pt;
    }

    .page-break {
      break-before: page;
    }

    @media print {
      body {
        background: #fff;
      }

      .page {
        max-width: none;
      }
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div class="page">
    <header class="hero">
      <p class="eyebrow">Project Dzukku Platform Brochure</p>
      <h1>Dzukku: An AI-Powered Restaurant Ordering, POS, and Operations Platform</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">
        A conversational food-ordering assistant connected to a complete restaurant control room:
        live orders, kitchen display, tables, reservations, delivery, payments, invoices, analytics,
        and automation.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-grid">
        <div class="hero-stat"><strong>AI Chat</strong><span>Telegram, WhatsApp, Swiggy, Zomato-ready flows</span></div>
        <div class="hero-stat"><strong>Live POS</strong><span>Admin, waiter, kitchen, and tracking portals</span></div>
        <div class="hero-stat"><strong>Realtime</strong><span>WebSocket events, KDS updates, order lifecycle</span></div>
        <div class="hero-stat"><strong>Data First</strong><span>PostgreSQL/SQLite, Excel, Google Sheets, n8n</span></div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <main>
      <section>
        <h2>Executive Overview</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          Dzukku is built for restaurants and cloud kitchens that want the convenience of aggregator-style ordering
          without losing their customer relationship, margin, or operational visibility. Customers place orders by
          simply chatting with an AI assistant. Staff manage the entire restaurant workflow from a React POS dashboard.
          The platform connects conversational ordering, restaurant operations, kitchen execution, reservations,
          payment readiness, delivery tracking, and business analytics into one ecosystem.
        </p>
        <p>
          The platform is especially suitable for the restaurant operations ecosystem because it does not treat ordering
          as a disconnected form. Every order moves through a complete journey: customer conversation, cart creation,
          confirmation, kitchen preparation, status updates, billing, delivery or service, reporting, and optional
          downstream automation.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>What This Application Includes</h2>
        <div class="grid-3">
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Customer AI Assistant</h3>
            <p>Customers can order, browse menus, ask for recommendations, reserve tables, and track progress through chat.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Natural-language ordering</li>
              <li>Mood, time, budget, and cuisine-aware suggestions</li>
              <li>Telegram and WhatsApp flows</li>
              <li>Swiggy and Zomato MCP/redirect support</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Restaurant POS</h3>
            <p>A staff-facing dashboard for day-to-day operations across admin, waiter, kitchen, delivery, and billing roles.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Order board and status chips</li>
              <li>Kitchen Display System</li>
              <li>Tables and dining sessions</li>
              <li>Invoices, settlements, staff, menu, analytics</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Operational Backend</h3>
            <p>A FastAPI service with structured models, authentication, real-time events, and durable order processing.</p>
            <ul>
              <li>REST APIs and WebSocket events</li>
              <li>JWT-protected staff access</li>
              <li>Outbox event pattern</li>
              <li>Excel, Google Sheets, n8n, Razorpay-ready integrations</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Core Platform Features</h2>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Area</th>
              <th>Feature Set</th>
              <th>Business Value</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>AI Ordering</strong></td>
              <td>Conversational menu discovery, cart management, confirmations, reservation booking, multilingual code-mix responses.</td>
              <td>Reduces friction and lets customers order the way they naturally speak.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Menu Intelligence</strong></td>
              <td>Live menu reads, item availability, category filters, fuzzy matching, alternatives, Excel-based menu seeding.</td>
              <td>Keeps AI responses grounded in actual restaurant data and current prices.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Kitchen Operations</strong></td>
              <td>KDS queues, item-level status, pending/cooking/done stages, kitchen load signals, expedite queue.</td>
              <td>Improves preparation visibility and reduces missed or delayed orders.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Dine-In Workflow</strong></td>
              <td>Table map, table sessions, waiter cart, guest count, fire-to-kitchen, invoice generation.</td>
              <td>Supports restaurant floor operations, not only delivery orders.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Delivery Workflow</strong></td>
              <td>Driver assignment, delivery status updates, GPS event model, proof of delivery columns, tracking page.</td>
              <td>Creates an end-to-end delivery experience from order to completion.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Payments & Billing</strong></td>
              <td>Payment intents, Razorpay integration readiness, paid state, invoices, settlements.</td>
              <td>Prepares the platform for real transaction handling and financial reconciliation.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Realtime Visibility</strong></td>
              <td>WebSocket broadcasting, order.created events, status_changed events, live dashboard refresh.</td>
              <td>Staff can react instantly when a chat order arrives or changes state.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Analytics</strong></td>
              <td>Revenue KPIs, top dishes, order trends, revenue-by-hour charts, historical Excel data.</td>
              <td>Turns operating data into decisions for menu planning and staffing.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <section class="page-break">
        <h2>How The AI Works</h2>
        <p>
          Dzukku's AI is designed as an agentic restaurant assistant, not a fixed FAQ bot. The language model handles
          conversation, intent, tone, and planning, while deterministic application code validates and commits business
          actions. This is important: the AI can suggest a tool call, but it cannot directly write arbitrary data,
          invent prices, or bypass order rules.
        </p>
        <div class="ai-flow">
          <div class="step"><strong>1. Context</strong>Reads customer, session, cart, history, menu, restaurant state, and order context.</div>
          <div class="step"><strong>2. Planner</strong>Gemini decides the customer goal and proposes actions such as add item or book table.</div>
          <div class="step"><strong>3. Executor</strong>Python validates items, prices, availability, payment readiness, and writes to the database.</div>
          <div class="step"><strong>4. Verifier</strong>The system re-reads committed data, recomputes totals, and checks the order summary.</div>
          <div class="step"><strong>5. Responder</strong>AI turns verified facts into a warm, concise reply in the customer's language style.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="callout" style="margin-top: 14px;">
          <strong>Principle:</strong> the LLM proposes; trusted code commits. This keeps the customer experience flexible
          while preserving accuracy for price, availability, payment, order status, and database writes.
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>AI Capabilities In Detail</h2>
        <div class="grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Natural Conversation</h3>
            <p>
              Customers do not need to learn a strict command syntax. They can type requests such as "show veg starters
              under 200", "I want something spicy", "same as last time", or "book a table for 4 tonight".
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Contextual Recommendations</h3>
            <p>
              The assistant can recommend food based on time of day, mood, celebration context, weather-style wording,
              budget, dietary preference, and previously known customer details.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Multilingual And Code-Mix Friendly</h3>
            <p>
              Dzukku is designed for real Indian chat behavior, including English, Hindi-English, and Telugu-English style
              conversations. It mirrors the user's pace and language instead of forcing a rigid app UI.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Tool-Grounded Accuracy</h3>
            <p>
              Food prices, menu items, cart totals, customer information, orders, and reservations are handled through
              tools backed by the database and menu source. The AI is not the source of financial truth.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Memory And Continuity</h3>
            <p>
              Sessions retain name, phone, cart, state, ordering platform, and rolling conversation history. A returning
              customer does not have to repeat basic details each time.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Safe Upselling</h3>
            <p>
              The assistant can suggest one relevant add-on, such as dessert, beverage, or combo, while keeping the
              conversation helpful rather than pushy.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Why It Fits The Restaurant Ecosystem</h2>
        <p>
          Restaurants need more than online ordering. They need an operating system that connects discovery, ordering,
          kitchen execution, dine-in service, delivery, reporting, and customer retention. Dzukku is suitable because it
          works at the intersection of customer experience and back-office discipline.
        </p>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Restaurant Need</th>
              <th>How Dzukku Supports It</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Lower dependency on aggregator commissions</td>
              <td>Direct chat ordering allows repeat customers to order from the restaurant without marketplace friction.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Fast service during peak hours</td>
              <td>Orders flow directly into POS and KDS; staff see queue state, preparation progress, and live updates.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Better customer retention</td>
              <td>The restaurant owns customer data, session memory, phone details, order history, and loyalty possibilities.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Operational clarity</td>
              <td>Dashboards show KPIs, order status, kitchen items, reservations, invoices, deliveries, and settlements.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Menu agility</td>
              <td>Excel-backed menu seeding and admin menu controls make price or availability changes easier to manage.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Multi-channel readiness</td>
              <td>Telegram, WhatsApp, Swiggy, Zomato, direct dine-in, delivery, and pickup can coexist under one platform model.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Human-like ordering experience</td>
              <td>AI handles natural language, mood, language mix, incomplete details, and conversational confirmations.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <section class="page-break">
        <h2>Customer Journey</h2>
        <div class="grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Direct Chat Order</h3>
            <ol>
              <li>Customer opens Telegram or WhatsApp from QR/link.</li>
              <li>Bot asks whether to order through Dzukku, Swiggy, or Zomato.</li>
              <li>Customer asks naturally for food or recommendations.</li>
              <li>AI calls menu/cart tools and confirms exact items and total.</li>
              <li>Bot collects missing name, phone, delivery/pickup details.</li>
              <li>Customer explicitly confirms.</li>
              <li>Order is saved and appears in the POS/KDS.</li>
            </ol>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Dine-In Or Reservation</h3>
            <ol>
              <li>Customer asks for a table date, time, and guest count.</li>
              <li>Bot asks only for missing fields and special requests.</li>
              <li>Reservation is committed with a reference number.</li>
              <li>Staff see booking in the reservations view.</li>
              <li>Waiter can open a table session and fire items to kitchen.</li>
              <li>Invoice is generated when service is complete.</li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Restaurant Staff Experience</h2>
        <div class="grid-3">
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Admin Portal</h3>
            <p>Dashboard, orders, deliveries, kitchen status, tables, reservations, menu, employees, invoices, settlements, and analytics.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Waiter Portal</h3>
            <p>Table map, active sessions, cart building, guest count, fire-to-kitchen workflow, and bill generation.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Kitchen Portal</h3>
            <p>Queued, cooking, and done columns with item-level progress, station filtering, and ready-to-serve/deliver flow.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Technology Architecture</h2>
        <div class="architecture">Customer Chat: Telegram / WhatsApp
        |
        v
Dzukku AI Bot: Gemini + LangGraph/ReAct + local tools + MCP tools
        |
        v
FastAPI Backend: Auth, Orders, Menu, Tables, Kitchen, Payments, Delivery, Invoices
        |
        +-- PostgreSQL / SQLite data layer
        +-- Excel menu and historical data
        +-- Google Sheets operational sync
        +-- Razorpay payment readiness
        +-- n8n workflow automation
        |
        v
React POS Frontend: Admin + Waiter + Kitchen + Tracking + Analytics
        |
        v
Realtime WebSocket events: order.created, order.status_changed, kitchen updates</div>
        <div class="badge-row">
          <span class="badge">React 19</span>
          <span class="badge">Vite</span>
          <span class="badge">FastAPI</span>
          <span class="badge">PostgreSQL</span>
          <span class="badge">SQLite</span>
          <span class="badge">Gemini 2.5 Flash</span>
          <span class="badge">LangGraph</span>
          <span class="badge">MCP</span>
          <span class="badge">WebSocket</span>
          <span class="badge">Razorpay-ready</span>
          <span class="badge">Google Sheets</span>
          <span class="badge">n8n</span>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Data, Safety, And Reliability</h2>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Control</th>
              <th>Purpose</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>JWT authentication</strong></td>
              <td>Protects staff routes and supports role-based access for admin, manager, kitchen, waiter, and related workflows.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Idempotency keys</strong></td>
              <td>Prevents duplicate order creation when a request is retried or submitted twice.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Outbox pattern</strong></td>
              <td>Keeps event delivery reliable by writing events with database transactions before broadcasting.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>LLM guardrails</strong></td>
              <td>Planner cannot directly commit financial or operational actions; executor validates all important writes.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Model fallback</strong></td>
              <td>Gemini primary model can fall back to alternate Gemini models if the primary path fails.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Offline queue</strong></td>
              <td>Frontend waiter flow can queue work locally and sync when connectivity returns.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <section class="page-break">
        <h2>Deployment Model</h2>
        <p>
          Dzukku can be deployed as a single-restaurant system first and then expanded into a multi-restaurant SaaS
          platform. The current application structure already separates the customer-facing bot, FastAPI backend,
          database, real-time layer, integrations, and React POS frontend, which makes deployment practical across
          cloud, VPS, or private restaurant infrastructure.
        </p>
        <div class="grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Single Restaurant Deployment</h3>
            <p>
              A small restaurant or cloud kitchen can run one backend service, one frontend deployment, one database,
              and one configured bot/channel. This is the fastest path for pilot launches and real restaurant testing.
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>Backend hosted with FastAPI and Uvicorn/Gunicorn.</li>
              <li>React POS built with Vite and served from static hosting or the backend server.</li>
              <li>Database deployed as PostgreSQL for production or SQLite for compact local pilots.</li>
              <li>Environment variables store tokens for Telegram, Gemini, Google Sheets, Razorpay, Twilio, and n8n.</li>
              <li>Restaurant menu is seeded from Excel and managed through POS menu tools.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Production Cloud Deployment</h3>
            <p>
              For production, Dzukku should run behind HTTPS with process supervision, backups, logging, and separate
              environments for development, staging, and production.
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>Containerize backend with Docker and deploy on AWS, Azure, GCP, Render, Railway, DigitalOcean, or a VPS.</li>
              <li>Use managed PostgreSQL with daily backups and migration control through Alembic.</li>
              <li>Serve frontend through Nginx, Vercel, Netlify, Cloudflare Pages, or S3-style static hosting.</li>
              <li>Use a reverse proxy for HTTPS, WebSocket upgrade headers, request limits, and health checks.</li>
              <li>Run background workers for outbox events, automations, and integration retries.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Layer</th>
              <th>Recommended Deployment Practice</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Backend API</td>
              <td>FastAPI service running in Docker, supervised by platform runtime, systemd, or Kubernetes.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Database</td>
              <td>Managed PostgreSQL for production; migrations through Alembic; encrypted backups and restore testing.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Frontend</td>
              <td>Vite production build served through static hosting or Nginx with API base URL configured per environment.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Bot Channels</td>
              <td>Telegram polling for simple pilots; webhooks for stronger production scaling; Twilio webhook for WhatsApp.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Realtime</td>
              <td>WebSocket endpoint behind HTTPS reverse proxy with reconnect logic already handled in the frontend.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Observability</td>
              <td>Structured logs, API health endpoint, order failure alerts, model error tracking, and integration retry logs.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Multi-Restaurant Platform Expansion</h2>
        <p>
          Dzukku can evolve from one restaurant into a platform serving many restaurants by making every major record
          tenant-aware. In the repository architecture this direction is already visible through restaurant-scoped models
          such as restaurants, users, customers, channels, menu categories, menu items, orders, payments, deliveries,
          tables, reservations, invoices, and outbox events.
        </p>
        <div class="architecture">Dzukku SaaS Control Plane
        |
        +-- Restaurant A
        |     +-- Own menu, staff, bot persona, tables, orders, customers, analytics
        |     +-- Telegram/WhatsApp channel A
        |
        +-- Restaurant B
        |     +-- Own menu, staff, bot persona, tables, orders, customers, analytics
        |     +-- Telegram/WhatsApp channel B
        |
        +-- Restaurant C
              +-- Own menu, staff, bot persona, tables, orders, customers, analytics
              +-- Telegram/WhatsApp channel C

Shared Platform Services: auth, billing, AI orchestration, integrations, monitoring, backups</div>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Capability</th>
              <th>How Multi-Restaurant Mode Works</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Tenant isolation</td>
              <td>Every operational object is scoped by restaurant_id so orders, menus, staff, tables, and analytics stay separated.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Restaurant onboarding</td>
              <td>Admin creates restaurant profile, uploads menu, configures opening hours, adds staff, and connects Telegram/WhatsApp channels.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Custom branding</td>
              <td>Each restaurant can have its own name, logo, tone, cuisine, greeting, offers, color theme, and assistant personality.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Separate operations</td>
              <td>Each restaurant gets its own POS views, KDS queue, table map, reservations, delivery workflow, invoices, and settlements.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Central owner dashboard</td>
              <td>A group owner can compare branches, revenue, top dishes, order load, staff performance, and customer retention across locations.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Shared platform cost</td>
              <td>AI, infrastructure, integration, and monitoring services can be shared while keeping restaurant data logically separated.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Multi-Agent AI Model</h2>
        <p>
          As the platform grows, Dzukku can use multiple specialized AI agents instead of one general bot. A coordinator
          agent can understand the customer's message and route work to focused agents for ordering, reservations,
          support, delivery, promotions, or analytics. This keeps the system easier to scale, test, and improve.
        </p>
        <div class="grid-3">
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Host / Router Agent</h3>
            <p>Identifies the restaurant, channel, customer intent, language, and next best workflow.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Menu Agent</h3>
            <p>Handles search, filters, dietary preferences, item alternatives, availability, and recommendation logic.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Ordering Agent</h3>
            <p>Manages cart, quantities, customer details, confirmation, idempotency, payment readiness, and order placement.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Reservation Agent</h3>
            <p>Handles date, time, guests, table availability, special requests, booking confirmation, and reminders.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Operations Agent</h3>
            <p>Assists staff with order status, kitchen load, delayed orders, delivery assignment, and manager alerts.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Analytics Agent</h3>
            <p>Answers business questions such as top dishes, peak hours, repeat customers, revenue, and menu performance.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="callout" style="margin-top: 14px;">
          <strong>Best architecture:</strong> one shared orchestration layer, many restaurant-specific personas, and
          multiple specialized agents. This allows Dzukku to serve different restaurant brands while keeping the core
          platform consistent and reliable.
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="page-break">
        <h2>Dzukku Compared With Aggregator Apps</h2>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Dimension</th>
              <th>Swiggy / Zomato Style</th>
              <th>Dzukku Style</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Customer entry</td>
              <td>App install, login, location, marketplace browsing.</td>
              <td>Open a chat link or QR and speak naturally.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Discovery</td>
              <td>Cards, filters, ads, ratings, long scroll journeys.</td>
              <td>Conversational suggestions based on preference, mood, budget, and time.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Restaurant economics</td>
              <td>Commission-heavy marketplace model.</td>
              <td>Direct customer relationship and lower dependency on third-party commissions.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Customer data</td>
              <td>Primarily owned by the aggregator platform.</td>
              <td>Restaurant owns operational data and can build loyalty directly.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Operations</td>
              <td>Separate partner dashboards and restaurant-side tools.</td>
              <td>POS, KDS, tables, reservations, billing, analytics, and AI in one ecosystem.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Best use case</td>
              <td>New customer discovery across many restaurants.</td>
              <td>Repeat customers, direct ordering, in-house operations, and relationship-driven service.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Use Cases</h2>
        <div class="grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Cloud Kitchen</h3>
            <p>Accept direct orders through chat, reduce marketplace dependency, track kitchen load, and manage delivery from one dashboard.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Dine-In Restaurant</h3>
            <p>Combine reservations, waiter table sessions, kitchen tickets, invoices, and customer follow-up in one platform.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>QSR / Cafe</h3>
            <p>Enable quick ordering, reordering, combo suggestions, and live preparation status for high-volume service.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Multi-Channel Ordering</h3>
            <p>Support direct Dzukku ordering while still giving customers Swiggy/Zomato paths when needed.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Implementation Strengths</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Full-stack coverage:</strong> customer bot, backend, POS frontend, kitchen, tables, delivery, and payment readiness.</li>
          <li><strong>AI with real controls:</strong> model reasoning is paired with deterministic execution and verification.</li>
          <li><strong>Real operational data model:</strong> restaurants, staff, customers, channels, sessions, carts, orders, payments, deliveries, tables, reservations, invoices, and outbox events.</li>
          <li><strong>Realtime by design:</strong> WebSocket events make orders visible to staff immediately.</li>
          <li><strong>Operator-friendly data:</strong> Excel and Google Sheets support non-technical restaurant workflows.</li>
          <li><strong>Deployment ready:</strong> Docker, PostgreSQL, Alembic migrations, environment-based configuration, and cloud/VPS deployment path.</li>
          <li><strong>Expansion path:</strong> MCP integrations, Razorpay, n8n, multi-role portals, multi-agent AI, and future multi-tenant capability.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Future Growth Opportunities</h2>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Opportunity</th>
              <th>Impact</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Loyalty and offers engine</td>
              <td>Personalized discounts, birthday offers, repeat-order campaigns, and customer segments.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Multi-restaurant SaaS mode</td>
              <td>Turn the platform into a repeatable product for many restaurants and cloud kitchens.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Multi-agent restaurant AI</td>
              <td>Use specialized AI agents for ordering, reservations, menu recommendations, delivery support, and analytics.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Branch-level deployment automation</td>
              <td>Onboard each restaurant or branch with a guided setup flow, generated bot credentials, menu import, and default POS configuration.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Inventory integration</td>
              <td>Stock-aware menu availability, purchase planning, and waste reduction.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Voice ordering</td>
              <td>Let customers or staff create orders through speech in noisy, fast-moving service contexts.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Advanced AI analytics</td>
              <td>Demand prediction, menu engineering, customer churn risk, and prep-time forecasting.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Summary</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          Dzukku is a practical AI restaurant ecosystem: friendly enough for customers, structured enough for staff,
          and technically grounded enough for real operations. Its biggest advantage is the bridge it creates between
          natural customer conversation and disciplined restaurant execution. A customer says what they want; Dzukku
          turns that into a verified order, kitchen workflow, billable transaction, and business record.
        </p>
        <div class="footer">
          Prepared for Project Dzukku. Source context: repository documentation, backend architecture, AI bot workflow,
          and React POS frontend structure.
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>
